      <h2>Marginal vs. Effective Tax Rate</h2>

      <p>
        This is one of the most misunderstood concepts in personal finance. Many people believe that if they
        are "in the 22% bracket," they pay 22% on all their income. That is not how it works.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Marginal tax rate</strong> is the rate you pay on your last (highest) dollar of income. It
        determines the tax impact of earning one more dollar or claiming one more dollar of deductions.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Effective tax rate</strong> is the total tax you owe divided by your total taxable income. It
        represents the blended, average rate across all brackets and is always lower than your marginal rate.
      </p>

      <h2>Step-by-Step Example: $100,000 Single Filer</h2>

      <p>
        Let us calculate the exact federal income tax for a single filer with $100,000 in gross income:
      </p>

      <h3>Step 1: Apply the Standard Deduction</h3>
      <p>$100,000 - $15,000 = <strong>$85,000 taxable income</strong></p>

      <h3>Step 2: Apply Each Bracket</h3>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Bracket</th>
            <th>Income in Bracket</th>
            <th>Tax</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>10% ($0 - $11,925)</td><td>$11,925</td><td>$1,192.50</td></tr>
          <tr><td>12% ($11,926 - $48,475)</td><td>$36,550</td><td>$4,386.00</td></tr>
          <tr><td>22% ($48,476 - $85,000)</td><td>$36,525</td><td>$8,035.50</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Total</strong></td><td><strong>$85,000</strong></td><td><strong>$13,614.00</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Step 3: Calculate Rates</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Marginal rate:</strong> 22% (the bracket containing the last dollar of income)</li>
        <li><strong>Effective rate on taxable income:</strong> $13,614 / $85,000 = 16.0%</li>
        <li><strong>Effective rate on gross income:</strong> $13,614 / $100,000 = 13.6%</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Even though this filer is "in the 22% bracket," they only pay an effective rate of 13.6% on their
        gross income. The first $15,000 is shielded by the standard deduction, the next $11,925 is taxed at
        10%, the next $36,550 at 12%, and only the final $36,525 is taxed at 22%.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Marginal Rates Matter for Decisions</h2>

      <p>
        Your marginal rate is the relevant number when evaluating tax-impacting decisions:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>401(k) contributions:</strong> A $1,000 traditional 401(k) contribution saves $220 in
          federal tax for someone in the 22% bracket. Use our
          <a href="/401k-calculator">401(k) calculator</a> to see your savings.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Roth vs. traditional:</strong> If you expect your marginal rate to be higher in retirement,
          Roth contributions are better. See our
          <a href="/guides/401k-vs-roth-ira">401(k) vs. Roth IRA guide</a>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Charitable giving:</strong> A $1,000 charitable deduction (if itemizing) saves $220 at the
          22% marginal rate but $370 at the 37% rate.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Side income:</strong> Extra freelance income of $5,000 will be taxed at your marginal rate
          plus <a href="/guides/self-employment-tax-explained">self-employment tax</a>.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Common Misconceptions</h2>

      <h3>"I don't want a raise because it will put me in a higher bracket"</h3>
      <p>
        Only the income within the new bracket is taxed at the higher rate. If you earn $48,475 (the top of
        the 12% bracket as a single filer) and get a $5,000 raise, only that $5,000 is taxed at 22%. Your
        total tax increases by $1,100, and you still take home an additional $3,900. You will never lose
        money by earning more due to bracket progression.
      </p>

      <h3>"Married filing jointly brackets are exactly double single brackets"</h3>
      <p>
        This is mostly true for the lower brackets, which is intentional to reduce the "marriage penalty."
        However, the 35% and 37% brackets for married filers are not exactly double the single filer
        brackets, creating a marriage penalty for very high earners.
      </p>

      <h2>How Brackets Interact with State Tax</h2>

      <p>
        Federal brackets only determine your federal income tax. State income tax is calculated separately
        using each state's own brackets and rules. Your total income tax is the sum of federal, state, and
        any local income taxes. See our <a href="/guides/state-tax-comparison">state tax comparison</a>
        for a complete overview.
      </p>

      <h2>Planning Around Bracket Boundaries</h2>

      <p>
        Smart tax planning involves keeping income below the next bracket when possible. Strategies include:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Maximizing traditional 401(k) or IRA contributions to reduce taxable income</li>
        <li>Timing income recognition (bonus deferral, stock option exercise timing)</li>
        <li>Accelerating or deferring deductions across tax years</li>
        <li>Contributing to an HSA if you have a high-deductible health plan</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Calculate your exact tax across all brackets using our
        <a href="/income-tax-calculator">income tax calculator</a> or see how brackets affect your paycheck
        with our <a href="/take-home-pay-calculator">take-home pay calculator</a>.
      </p>
